254
0:10:39.26,000 --> 0:10:41,000
and when they've doubled in size, you'll see them split,

255
0:10:41.26,000 --> 0:10:43,000
and that's how they reproduce and the population grows.

256
0:10:43.26,000 --> 0:10:46,000
But suppose then that one of them mutates.

257
0:10:46.26,000 --> 0:10:48,000
There's a mutation in the gene

258
0:10:48.26,000 --> 0:10:5,000
and one of them mutates to follow a selfish strategy.

259
0:10:50.26,000 --> 0:10:52,000
It takes advantage of the others.

260
0:10:52.26,000 --> 0:10:55,000
And so when a green interacts with a blue,

261
0:10:55.26,000 --> 0:10:57,000
you'll see the green gets larger and the blue gets smaller.

262
0:10:57.26,000 --> 0:10:59,000
So here's how things play out.

263
0:10:59.26,000 --> 0:11:01,000
We start with just one green,

264
0:11:01.26,000 --> 0:11:03,000
and as it interacts

265
0:11:03.26,000 --> 0:11:06,000
it gains wealth or points or food.

266
0:11:06.26,000 --> 0:11:09,000
And in short order, the cooperators are done for.

267
0:11:09.26,000 --> 0:11:12,000
The free-riders have taken over.

268
0:11:12.26,000 --> 0:11:15,000
If a group cannot solve the free-rider problem

269
0:11:15.26,000 --> 0:11:18,000
then it cannot reap the benefits of cooperation

270
0:11:18.26,000 --> 0:11:21,000
and group selection cannot get started.

271
0:11:21.26,000 --> 0:11:23,000
But there are solutions to the free-rider problem.

272
0:11:23.26,000 --> 0:11:25,000
It's not that hard a problem.

273
0:11:25.26,000 --> 0:11:28,000
In fact, nature has solved it many, many times.

274
0:11:28.26,000 --> 0:11:3,000
And nature's favorite solution

275
0:11:30.26,000 --> 0:11:33,000
is to put everyone in the same boat.

276
0:11:33.26,000 --> 0:11:35,000
For example,

277
0:11:35.26,000 --> 0:11:38,000
why is it that the mitochondria in every cell

278
0:11:38.26,000 --> 0:11:4,000
has its own DNA,

279
0:11:40.26,000 --> 0:11:43,000
totally separate from the DNA in the nucleus?

280
0:11:43.26,000 --> 0:11:45,000
It's because they used to be

281
0:11:45.26,000 --> 0:11:47,000
separate free-living bacteria

282
0:11:47.26,000 --> 0:11:49,000
and they came together

283
0:11:49.26,000 --> 0:11:51,000
and became a superorganism.

284
0:11:51.26,000 --> 0:11:54,000
Somehow or other -- maybe one swallowed another; we'll never know exactly why --

285
0:11:54.26,000 --> 0:11:56,000
but once they got a membrane around them,

286
0:11:56.26,000 --> 0:11:58,000
they were all in the same membrane,

287
0:11:58.26,000 --> 0:12:01,000
now all the wealth-created division of labor,

288
0:12:01.26,000 --> 0:12:03,000
all the greatness created by cooperation,

289
0:12:03.26,000 --> 0:12:05,000
stays locked inside the membrane

290
0:12:05.26,000 --> 0:12:08,000
and we've got a superorganism.

291
0:12:08.26,000 --> 0:12:1,000
And now let's rerun the simulation

292
0:12:10.26,000 --> 0:12:12,000
putting one of these superorganisms

293
0:12:12.26,000 --> 0:12:15,000
into a population of free-riders, of defectors, of cheaters

294
0:12:15.26,000 --> 0:12:18,000
and look what happens.

295
0:12:18.26,000 --> 0:12:2,000
A superorganism can basically take what it wants.

296
0:12:20.26,000 --> 0:12:23,000
It's so big and powerful and efficient

297
0:12:23.26,000 --> 0:12:25,000
that it can take resources

298
0:12:25.26,000 --> 0:12:29,000
from the greens, from the defectors, the cheaters.

299
0:12:29.26,000 --> 0:12:31,000
And pretty soon the whole population

300
0:12:31.26,000 --> 0:12:34,000
is actually composed of these new superorganisms.

301
0:12:34.26,000 --> 0:12:36,000
What I've shown you here

302
0:12:36.26,000 --> 0:12:38,000
is sometimes called a major transition

303
0:12:38.26,000 --> 0:12:41,000
in evolutionary history.

304
0:12:41.26,000 --> 0:12:43,000
Darwin's laws don't change,

305
0:12:43.26,000 --> 0:12:46,000
but now there's a new kind of player on the field

306
0:12:46.26,000 --> 0:12:49,000
and things begin to look very different.

307
0:12:49.26,000 --> 0:12:51,000
Now this transition was not a one-time freak of nature

308
0:12:51.26,000 --> 0:12:53,000
that just happened with some bacteria.

309
0:12:53.26,000 --> 0:12:55,000
It happened again

310
0:12:55.26,000 --> 0:12:57,000
about 120 or a 140 million years ago

311
0:12:57.26,000 --> 0:13:,000
when some solitary wasps

312
0:13:00.26,000 --> 0:13:02,000
began creating little simple, primitive

313
0:13:02.26,000 --> 0:13:05,000
nests, or hives.

314
0:13:05.26,000 --> 0:13:08,000
Once several wasps were all together in the same hive,

315
0:13:08.26,000 --> 0:13:1,000
they had no choice but to cooperate,

316
0:13:10.26,000 --> 0:13:12,000
because pretty soon they were locked into competition

317
0:13:12.26,000 --> 0:13:14,000
with other hives.

318
0:13:14.26,000 --> 0:13:16,000
And the most cohesive hives won,

319
0:13:16.26,000 --> 0:13:18,000
just as Darwin said.

320
0:13:18.26,000 --> 0:13:2,000
These early wasps

321
0:13:20.26,000 --> 0:13:22,000
gave rise to the bees and the ants

322
0:13:22.26,000 --> 0:13:24,000
that have covered the world

323
0:13:24.26,000 --> 0:13:26,000
and changed the biosphere.

324
0:13:26.26,000 --> 0:13:28,000
And it happened again,

325
0:13:28.26,000 --> 0:13:3,000
even more spectacularly,

326
0:13:30.26,000 --> 0:13:32,000
in the last half-million years

327
0:13:32.26,000 --> 0:13:34,000
when our own ancestors

328
0:13:34.26,000 --> 0:13:36,000
became cultural creatures,

329
0:13:36.26,000 --> 0:13:39,000
they came together around a hearth or a campfire,

330
0:13:39.26,000 --> 0:13:41,000
they divided labor,

331
0:13:41.26,000 --> 0:13:44,000
they began painting their bodies, they spoke their own dialects,

332
0:13:44.26,000 --> 0:13:47,000
and eventually they worshiped their own gods.

333
0:13:47.26,000 --> 0:13:49,000
Once they were all in the same tribe,

334
0:13:49.26,000 --> 0:13:52,000
they could keep the benefits of cooperation locked inside.

335
0:13:52.26,000 --> 0:13:54,000
And they unlocked the most powerful force

336
0:13:54.26,000 --> 0:13:56,000
ever known on this planet,

337
0:13:56.26,000 --> 0:13:58,000
which is human cooperation --

338
0:13:58.26,000 --> 0:14:,000
a force for construction

339
0:14:00.26,000 --> 0:14:03,000
and destruction.

340
0:14:03.26,000 --> 0:14:05,000
Of course, human groups are nowhere near as cohesive

341
0:14:05.26,000 --> 0:14:07,000
as beehives.

342
0:14:07.26,000 --> 0:14:1,000
Human groups may look like hives for brief moments,

343
0:14:10.26,000 --> 0:14:12,000
but they tend to then break apart.

344
0:14:12.26,000 --> 0:14:15,000
We're not locked into cooperation the way bees and ants are.

345
0:14:15.26,000 --> 0:14:17,000
In fact, often,

346
0:14:17.26,000 --> 0:14:19,000
as we've seen happen in a lot of the Arab Spring revolts,

347
0:14:19.26,000 --> 0:14:23,000
often those divisions are along religious lines.

348
0:14:23.26,000 --> 0:14:26,000
Nonetheless, when people do come together

349
0:14:26.26,000 --> 0:14:28,000
and put themselves all into the same movement,

350
0:14:28.26,000 --> 0:14:31,000
they can move mountains.

351
0:14:31.26,000 --> 0:14:34,000
Look at the people in these photos I've been showing you.

352
0:14:34.26,000 --> 0:14:36,000
Do you think they're there

353
0:14:36.26,000 --> 0:14:38,000
pursuing their self-interest?

354
0:14:38.26,000 --> 0:14:41,000
Or are they pursuing communal interest,

355
0:14:41.26,000 --> 0:14:44,000
which requires them to lose themselves

356
0:14:44.26,000 --> 0:14:48,000
and become simply a part of a whole?

357
0:14:49.26,000 --> 0:14:51,000
Okay, so that was my Talk

358
0:14:51.26,000 --> 0:14:53,000
delivered in the standard TED way.

359
0:14:53.26,000 --> 0:14:55,000
And now I'm going to give the whole Talk over again

360
0:14:55.26,000 --> 0:14:57,000
in three minutes

361
0:14:57.26,000 --> 0:15:,000
in a more full-spectrum sort of way.

